<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
My wife and I have talked about the druid charm spells before (read she listened to me whine about how useless they are) and we came up with a reasonable improvement that<BR>we feel doesn't unbalance the game.<P>Our idea is that animals that are friendly (indifferent and higher?) to the druid stay friendly after the charm breaks.  In these cases, the charm would be more akin to the druid using her special relationship with the animal kingdom to have the animal do her favors -- the animal being more than happy to do so and thus not grumpy when the spell breaks.<P>Animals that weren't friendly (lower than indifferent?) before the charm would still attack you when the charm breaks.<P>Because most (all?) of the more powerful animals in the game aren't all that friendly even to druids, this would prevent, say, a druid from charming a griffon and wiping out an entire zone without fear of reprisal.<P>I can't imagine this would be difficult to implement.<P>I know it would make me feel at least a little better about our charms.<BR><P>------------------<BR>Faolan De'Danaan<BR>28th Level Druid<BR>Fennin Ro
</FONT>
